<dl class="specification-list">

        <dt>Identification and Creation</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>1943.861</dd>

                            <dt>People</dt>
                <dd>
                                                                 <a href=https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/collections/person/26693>Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres</a>, French                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          (Montauban 1780 - 1867 Paris)
                                            <br>
                                    </dd>
            
                            <dt>Title</dt>
                <dd>Studies of a Man and a Woman for "The Golden Age"</dd>
            
                                                                                                            
                            <dt>Classification</dt>
                <dd>Drawings</dd>
                                        <dt>Work Type</dt>
                <dd>
                                                            drawing                                                      </dd>
                                        <dt>Date</dt>
                <dd>1843-1848</dd>
                                                                <dt>Culture</dt>
                <dd>French</dd>
                            <dt>Persistent Link</dt>
                <dd><a href="https://hvrd.art/o/299799">https://hvrd.art/o/299799</a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
                <dt>Physical Descriptions</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Medium</dt>
              <dd>Graphite on cream wove paper, backed, traced with a stylus after mounting, squared</dd>
            
           
           
                          <dt>Dimensions</dt>
              <dd>41.6 x 31.5 cm (16 3/8 x 12 3/8 in.)<br />
frame: 64.7 x 51.9 x 2.9 cm (25 1/2 x 20 7/16 x 1 1/8 in.)</dd>
            
            
            
            
            
                          <dt>Inscriptions and Marks</dt>
              <dd>
                                  <ul class="unstyled-list">
                                          <li data-a="1">
                        Signed: graphite, l.l.: Ingres
                      </li>
                    
                    
                    
                                      </ul>
                              </dd>
            
          </dl>
        </dd>
        
                  <dt>Provenance</dt>
          <dd>Sold by the artist to Étienne-François Haro, October 13, 1866; consigned by him to the Ingres sale, Drouot, Paris, May 6-7, 1867, no. 45 (Fr 800); purchased by comte Louis-Alexandre Foucher de Careil; with Haro again by 1870; acquired through Martin Birnbaum by Grenville L. Winthrop, January 1936 (Fr 18,000); his bequest to the Fogg Art Museum, 1943.</dd>
        
        
        
        <dt>Acquisition and Rights</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Credit Line</dt>
              <dd>Harvard Art Museums/Fogg Museum, Bequest of Grenville L. Winthrop</dd>
            
            
                          <dt>Accession Year</dt>
              <dd>1943</dd>
            
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>1943.861</dd>

                          <dt>Division</dt>
              <dd>European and American Art</dd>
            
                          <dt>Contact</dt>
              <dd><a href="mailto:am_europeanamerican@harvard.edu"><span>am_europeanamerican@harvard.edu</span></a></dd>
                                      <dd>THIS WORK MAY NOT BE LENT BY THE TERMS OF ITS ACQUISITION TO THE HARVARD ART MUSEUMS.</dd>
                   		  <dd>The Harvard Art Museums encourage the use of images found on this website for personal, noncommercial use, including educational and scholarly purposes. To request a higher resolution file of this image, please submit an <a href="https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/imagerequest"><span>online request.</span></a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
